<br>
Economic woes: If you are blaming the most-recent bear market on the Presidential uncertainty last year, then I advise you to look elsewhere. The reason why capital markets work is because they are true markets - they reflect true risk versus reward with minimum government interference. During Clinton's terms investors (or speculators if you rather) pumped trillions into tech stocks on the premise that they would be profitable one day. Ten years later most of these companies have yet to make a cent, and investors gradually took their money out. Here is your real culprit.<br>
<br>
Recession?: A Dow that trades at 9500 or a NASDAQ at 1800 does not mean we are in recession. In fact, if economic growth is still rising while unemployemnt, inflation, and interest rates remain in check, then it's hard to say we are heading towards a recession. Granted many investors may be losing money in the stock markets, but that doesn't mean our overall economy is suffering.<br>
<br>
Presidential elections: In fact, three elections in US history have resulted with the winner receiving fewer popular votes than his opponent. If memory serves, this dubious trio consists of Andrew Jackson, Rutherford B. Hayes, and Benjamin Harrison. The electoral college was set up to allow smaller states a larger say in the election.<br>
<br>
Many Presidents have won without receiving a majority of the popular vote. This usually occurs when there is a strong third party candidate involved such as Teddy Roosevelt or Ross Perot. This is where the electoral college works its magic. Each state can have only one winner. Thus we are assured of a President, even if a zillion people run for office.<br>
<br>
Presidential power: Despite what they teach kids in US government classes today, the President is far more than 1/3 of the political power in our country. Although he solely controls the Executive branch, don't forget that he appoints members to the Judicial branch and has great influence on what laws gets passed and who gets elected to the Legislative branch. Make no doubt about it, the President of the United States wields tremendous power.<br>
<br>
Summary: If you are taking a beating in the stock market, George W has little to do with it. Markets behave according to the laws of economics because, well, our markets work. Capitalism, democracy, and a little laissez-faire is the magic combination. Instead, try looking at your portfolio or the asset allocations in your mutual funds. It you see a bunch of dot.coms, then there's your answer. No President in the world is gonna be able to keep a company's stock price at $100 bil when it's really worth $10 bil. And therein lies the true question...how much is my stock really worth? No wonder MBAs are in such demand now.<br>
<br>
-Delilah<br>
